UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 AN ACT relating to prison educational programs.
2 Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of Kentucky:
3 SECTION 1. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 197 IS CREATED TO
4 READ AS FOLLOWS:
5 (1) The Kentucky Community and Technical College System Prison Education
6 Program, or KCTCS Prison Education Program, is hereby established within the
7 department to provide inmates with intensive, hands-on job training in high-
8 demand workforce sectors.
9 (2) The department shall enter into a memorandum of agreement with the Kentucky
10 Community and Technical College System (KCTCS) as defined in KRS 164.001
11 in accordance with Section 2 of this Act to provide academic instruction for the
12 program.
13 (3) (a) The program established in subsection (1) of this section shall be located on
14 the grounds of the Northpoint Training Center.
15 (b) The department shall:
16 1. Manage facility operations, including operations related to safety and
17 security;
18 2. Be responsible for all maintenance and repair of the facility, utilities,
19 and facility supplies; and
20 3. Provide inmate transportation to the facility, inmate meals and food
21 services, and inmate housing that is segregated from the general
22 prison population.
23 (4) The program shall not be available to an inmate serving a sentence:
24 (a) Of imprisonment for life without possibility of parole;
25 (b) For escape or attempted escape; or
26 (c) For a sex crime as defined in KRS 17.500.
27 (5) (a) The department shall be responsible for the identification of candidates for
Page 1 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 the program, including recruitment and selection, in accordance with the
2 restrictions set forth in subsection (4) of this section and as determined by
3 the department.
4 (b) Selection of candidates for the program shall include consideration of:
5 1. Established security criteria;
6 2. Industry guidance for second-chance employment; and
7 3. The capacity of academic instructors to provide industry-
8 recommended and high-need training.
9 (6) An inmate who is selected and meets eligibility requirements shall be transported
10 by the department to the Northpoint Training Center facility.
11 (7) The department shall promulgate administrative regulations in accordance with
12 KRS Chapter 13A relating to:
13 (a) The selection and eligibility of inmates for the program, including but not
14 limited to the following criteria:
15 1. The inmate's academic background;
16 2. Vocational counseling or testing that indicates the inmate has an
17 interest or aptitude for a particular trade; and
18 3. The inmate's willingness to abide by the attendance, academic, and
19 behavioral requirements of the program;
20 (b) The terms and conditions under which inmates may continue in the
21 program;
22 (c) The adequate care, supervision, guarding, disciplining, maintenance,
23 transportation, and housing of inmates when assigned to the program;
24 (d) Availability and accessibility of post-release services, including
25 consideration of education and employment requirements in administering
26 terms of probation and parole;
27 (e) The collection of data to include:
Page 2 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 1. The number of inmates:
2 a. Participating in the program who receive an offer of employment
3 prior to release;
4 b. Who successfully complete the program;
5 c. Who obtained employment following participation in the
6 program; and
7 d. Who were unsuccessful and the reason for removal from the
8 program; and
9 2. Following completion of the program and release from the facility, the
10 number of inmates with:
11 a. Successful completion of parole;
12 b. A violation of parole;
13 c. A return to prison as a result of a parole violation and the date
14 the inmate returned; and
15 d. A return to prison as a result of the commission of a new
16 offense;
17 (f) Requirements of KCTCS employees, including:
18 1. Compliance with the department's institutional safety and facilities
19 management policies and procedures; and
20 2. Participation in the department's drug-testing program, including
21 random screenings and tests based upon reasonable suspicion of drug
22 or alcohol impairment, as determined by the warden of the institution,
23 and at the cost of the department if the test is administered at a
24 department facility by a department vendor;
25 (g) Policies to permit remote instruction or services during emergencies or
26 pandemics, consistent with department and health advisories of the
27 Commonwealth; and
Page 3 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 (h) Any other regulations the department deems necessary and appropriate to
2 carry out the requirements of this section.
3 (8) Hours of classroom instruction shall model, to the extent possible, an average
4 workday similar to what the inmate can expect to experience in employment upon
5 release.
6 (9) Instruction shall occur outside of any area accessible by the general population
7 of the facility and inmates participating in the program shall be segregated from
8 the general prison population at all times.
9 (10) Potential employers shall have the opportunity to recruit and interview potential
10 employees prior to parole.
11 (11) KCTCS shall:
12 (a) Construct a facility on the grounds of Northpoint Training Center to
13 provide academic instruction for the prison education program established
14 in this section;
15 (b) Upon completion of the facility construction under paragraph (a) of this
16 subsection, deed the facility to the department which will bear responsibility
17 for management, operations, security, and maintenance. The details of the
18 prison education program will be jointly determined by the department and
19 KCTCS outlined in a memorandum of agreement between the parties;
20 (c) Retain ownership, maintenance, and responsibility for all equipment related
21 to academic instruction within the prison education program;
22 (d) Ensure compliance with all applicable federal, state, and local laws;
23 (e) Enter into and maintain all appropriate confidentiality and data protection
24 agreements, including nondisclosure forms, for all academic instruction
25 employees accessing Commonwealth data;
26 (f) Provide academic instruction within the facility and all components
27 required for instruction, including a learning management system; and
Page 4 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 (g) Determine program placement with regard to a participant's academic
2 readiness.
3 (12) This section shall not be interpreted to:
4 (a) Create or confer upon any inmate any private right or benefit; or
5 (b) Limit the discretion of the department in determining and maintaining
6 operational and security requirements of the department.
7 SECTION 2. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 197 IS CREATED TO
8 READ AS FOLLOWS:
9 (1) The memorandum of agreement required under Section 1 of this Act between the
10 department and the Kentucky Community and Technical College System
11 (KCTCS):
12 (a) Shall establish the duties and responsibilities of each party; and
13 (b) May be amended by the parties as necessary, including the addition of terms
14 not required under this section, to meet the needs of the program.
15 (2) The duties and responsibilities of the department shall include:
16 (a) Establishing rules of conduct for inmates participating in the program and
17 maintaining decision-making authority related to any disciplinary action for
18 violations of the rules established under this paragraph;
19 (b) Marketing the program across correctional facilities throughout the
20 Commonwealth with inmates who may meet eligibility requirements;
21 (c) Providing training for each college employee entering the facility or
22 communicating with an inmate, including necessary training related to
23 safety, security, and relevant policies and procedures;
24 (d) Providing training for each college employee entering the facility or
25 communicating with a participating inmate virtually or in a distance
26 format;
27 (e) For the training required under paragraphs (c) and (d) of this subsection,
Page 5 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 providing modules related to:
2 1. Safety, security, and related policies and procedures;
3 2. The Prison Rape Elimination Act, 34 U.S.C. sec. 30301 et seq.;
4 3. Maintaining professional boundaries; and
5 4. The use of core correctional practices to effectively respond to
6 behavior;
7 (f) Providing KCTCS with necessary data to operate the program, including:
8 1. The transfer and release dates of inmates participating in the program
9 as required by the United States Secretary of Education under 34
10 C.F.R. sec. 668.239;
11 2. A roster of inmates approved for the program to be submitted to the
12 college's designated office for each term;
13 3. Grades and course completions entered into the Kentucky Offender
14 Management System;
15 4. Information to determine the last day of attendance; and
16 5. Information to assist in tracking graduates post-release;
17 (g) Helping to facilitate required verification, identification, and financial aid
18 documents with identified federal agencies for participation in the program;
19 (h) Providing operational support to successfully carry out the program,
20 including:
21 1. Adequate security staffing to support the inmates participating in the
22 program at the KCTCS Prison Education Program campus and
23 collaborating with external partners on reentry services;
24 2. Office space, copier access, and utilities at no cost to KCTCS;
25 3. Clear processes and systems to pay for education expenses, for use by
26 inmates participating in the program;
27 4. Background checks of all KCTCS employees using the department's
Page 6 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 approved vendors and processes;
2 5. Maintenance and replacement of learning technology onsite to ensure
3 continuity in the learning environment when technology
4 malfunctions, including the use of department-issued tablets; and
5 6. Facilitating the purchase and acquisition of class supplies at the
6 beginning of each academic term and charging the cost, along with
7 books, to the participating inmate's financial aid account; and
8 (i) Participating in joint meetings between the department and KCTCS to
9 review program outcomes, security issues, and facility updates each term.
10 (3) The duties and responsibilities of KCTCS shall include:
11 (a) Establishing rules of academic conduct for inmates participating in the
12 program and maintaining decision-making authority related to any
13 disciplinary action for violations of the rules established under this
14 paragraph;
15 (b) Ensuring compliance with all applicable federal, state, and local laws
16 related to student privacy and department security procedures;
17 (c) Maintaining all instructional equipment that is provided by KCTCS within
18 the facility, outside of learning technology that is part of the prison
19 environment;
20 (d) Providing marketing support for the program including:
21 1. Brand guidelines;
22 2. Program information;
23 3. Transfer pathways; and
24 4. Public relations requests related to the program;
25 (e) Developing and distributing a specific catalog or similar publication
26 describing available programs, services for inmates participating in the
27 program, curriculum maps, and delivery options;
