1 b. Performance of the participating inmate;
2 c. Syllabi review; and
3 d. Faculty observation;
4 (h) Providing and managing staffing related to the academic components of the
5 program, including:
6 1. Qualified and credentialed in-person and online instructors for
7 coursework; and
8 2. Admissions, financial aid, advising, online library, tutoring, veteran
9 support, transcript collection, and academic support services on-site at
10 the facility;
11 (i) Ensuring compliance with requirements of the Southern Association of
12 Colleges and Schools Commission on Colleges and requirements of the
13 Department of Education for the program;
14 (j) Providing graduation ceremonies on-site; and
15 (k) Working with the department and external partners to match inmates who
16 have completed the program with employers and collecting and reporting
17 job placement and data transfer on an annual basis.
18 (4) The department and KCTCS shall negotiate the responsibility for the cost of
19 licensing and certification examinations if required by an academic program
20 offered in the facility.
21 (5) This section shall not be interpreted to:
22 (a) Create or confer upon any inmate any private right or benefit; or
23 (b) Limit the discretion of the department in determining and maintaining
24 operational and security requirements of the department.
25 Section 3. KRS 196.281 is amended to read as follows:
26 (1) When a prisoner is released, the department shall issue to that prisoner, with the
27 prisoner's consent, documents regarding all of the following:
Page 9 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 (a) The prisoner's criminal history in Kentucky;
2 (b) The prisoner's institutional history, including all of the following:
3 1. Any record of major disciplinary violations;
4 2. Whether the prisoner successfully completed programming approved by
5 the department;
6 3. Whether the prisoner obtained a high school equivalency diploma or
7 other educational degree prior to incarceration, to the extent known or
8 verifiable by the department;
9 4. Whether the prisoner obtained a high school equivalency diploma or
10 other educational degree while incarcerated;
11 5. The prisoner's work record prior to incarceration, including past
12 employment and skills, to the extent known or verifiable by the
13 department, and to the extent the department is technologically capable
14 of providing this information; and
15 6. The prisoner's institutional work record, including skills obtained
16 through any job training or programming provided by the department;
17 and
18 (c) Other information considered relevant by the department.
19 (2) When a prisoner is released, the department may, in conjunction with the
20 Transportation Cabinet, issue to that prisoner an operator's license or personal
21 identification card that is a voluntary travel ID document pursuant to KRS 186.417.
22 (3) In addition to the documents provided under subsections (1) and (2) of this section,
23 the department shall issue a certificate of employability to a prisoner if all of the
24 following apply:
25 (a) The prisoner achieved one (1) or both of the following:
26 1. While incarcerated:[,]
27 a. Successfully earned one (1) or more of the following:
Page 10 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 i.[a.] An educational credit pursuant to KRS 197.045(1)(a)2.;
2 ii.[b.] A program completion credit pursuant to KRS
3 197.045(1)(a)3.; or
4 iii.[c.] A work-for-time credit pursuant to KRS 197.047; or
5 b. Successfully completed the Kentucky Community and Technical
6 College System Prison Education Program pursuant to Section 1
7 of this Act; or
8 2. Prior to incarceration, earned a High School Equivalency Diploma, a
9 high school diploma, a college degree, certification from a vocational or
10 technical education program that the program was completed, or a
11 diploma or degree from a correspondence postsecondary education
12 program approved by the department;
13 (b) The prisoner received no major disciplinary violations during the year
14 immediately preceding his or her release; and
15 (c) 1. The prisoner received a score or level of competence as determined by
16 the department on a job skills assessment test administered by the
17 department or jail; or
18 2. The prisoner successfully completed the KCTCS Prison Education
19 Program and received an academic certificate, diploma, or degree.
20 (4) A certificate of employability issued pursuant to subsection (3) of this section shall:
21 (a) Be issued to the prisoner when he or she is released from a correctional
22 facility;
23 (b) Be on a form provided by the department;
24 (c) Be valid unless revoked by the department; and
25 (d) Not create relief from:
26 1. A requirement to register as a sex offender under KRS 17.510;
27 2. A driver's license, commercial driver's license, or probationary license
Page 11 of 15
HB000510.100 - 1335 - XXXX 3/31/2026 8:45 PM GA

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS HB 5/GA
1 suspension, cancellation, or revocation;
2 3. A restriction on employment as a prosecutor or law enforcement officer;
3 or
4 4. The denial, ineligibility, or automatic suspension of a health care
5 professional's license due to a substance use disorder.
6 (5) (a) The department shall revoke the certificate of employability provided under
7 this section of any individual who is convicted of a felony after receiving a
8 certificate of employability.
9 (b) The department shall provide an individual whose certificate of employability
10 has been revoked under this subsection an opportunity to file a grievance
11 through the department's prisoner grievance system. The revocation of a
12 certificate of employability is effective when the individual is notified of the
13 revocation.
14 (c) The revocation of a certificate of employability does not affect the right of an
15 employer to rely on the validity of the certificate of employability unless the
16 employer knew before the individual was employed that the certificate of
17 employability was fraudulent.
18 (6) An individual shall not intentionally state or otherwise represent that he or she has a
19 valid certificate of employability issued by the department knowing that the
20 statement or representation is false. An individual who violates this subsection shall
21 be guilty of a Class B misdemeanor.
22 (7) Upon request, the department shall confirm whether a certificate of employability
23 has been issued to a named individual and whether the certificate is valid at the time
24 of the inquiry and at the time of the department's response to that inquiry.
25 (8) The department is not civilly liable for damages based upon its decision to issue or
26 deny issuance of a certificate of employability to any prisoner or for revoking or
27 failing to revoke a certificate of employability issued to any prisoner.
