1 (9) (a) In a judicial or administrative proceeding alleging negligence or other fault, a
2 certificate of employability issued to an individual under this section may be
3 introduced as evidence of a person's due care in hiring, retaining, licensing,
4 leasing to, admitting to a school or program, or otherwise transacting business
5 or engaging in activity with the individual to whom the certificate of
6 employability was issued if the person knew of the certificate at the time of
7 the alleged negligence or other fault.
8 (b) In any proceeding on a claim against an employer for negligent hiring, a
9 certificate of employability issued to an individual under this section may be a
10 defense for the employer as to the claim if the employer knew of the
11 certificate at the time of the alleged negligence, except in cases where the
12 employer knew or should have known the employee should not be hired for
13 the position due to the nature of his or her history, including criminal history
14 relevant to the claim.
15 (10) The department shall notify incoming prisoners of the possibility to earn a
16 certificate of employability.
17 (11) The department shall submit an annual report no later than September 1 of each
18 year to the Governor and to the Legislative Research Commission for referral to
19 the Interim Joint Committee on Licensing, Occupations, and Administrative
20 Regulations and the Interim Joint Committee on Judiciary[General Assembly],
21 which shall include:
22 (a) The number of certificates of employability issued in the preceding twelve
23 (12) months;[,]
24 (b) The rate of recidivism among released prisoners previously issued certificates
25 of employability;[, and]
26 (c) Any other information the department deems appropriate to include; and
27 (d) Beginning September 1, 2029, the data in subsection (7)(e) of Section 1 of
